      "title": "Man Arrested Following Thefts in Bamford Area",
      "slug": "government-plans-to-change-law-to-deport-rochdale-rapist",
      "excerpt": "Home Secretary Shabana Mahmood has outlined plans to deport Shabir Ahmed, the leader of the Rochdale grooming gang, following his release from prison after serving 14 years for multiple sexual offences.",
      "content_html": "<p class=\"ongoing-label\"><strong>ONGOING STORY</strong> — Updated 20 July 2026 at 11:30. 90 source updates have been combined into this article.</p><p>Home Secretary Shabana Mahmood has outlined plans to deport Shabir Ahmed, the leader of the Rochdale grooming gang, following his release from prison after serving 14 years for multiple sexual offences.</p><h2>Latest update</h2><p>Shabana Mahmood, the Home Secretary, has announced plans to amend the Immigration Act 1971 to enable the deportation of serious foreign criminals, including Shabir Ahmed, the ringleader of the Rochdale grooming gang.</p><p>Ahmed, 73, was released from prison this month after serving 14 years of a 22-year sentence for 30 child rape offences. Despite being stripped of his UK citizenship, he cannot be returned to Pakistan due to a legal loophole that exempts Commonwealth citizens from removal if they arrived in the UK before 1973 and have lived here for at least five years.</p><p>The proposed changes will disapply this exemption for individuals convicted of serious crimes such as child grooming, human trafficking, and war crimes. Mahmood assured MPs that the amendments would not affect the protections provided to other Commonwealth citizens, including the Windrush generation.</p><p>The legal change follows calls from both Labour and Conservative MPs, as well as victims, for Ahmed to be deported from the UK. Mahmood stated that the threshold for this power would be linked to the ability to deprive citizenship, which applies only in cases of exceptional severity.</p><h2>Earlier developments</h2><p>Home Secretary Shabana Mahmood has outlined plans to deport Shabir Ahmed, the leader of the Rochdale grooming gang, following his release from prison after serving 14 years for multiple sexual offences.</p><p>Home Secretary Shabana Mahmood has announced proposed changes to immigration laws that could enable the deportation of Shabir Ahmed, the leader of the Rochdale grooming gang. Ahmed was released from prison on 2 July after serving 14 years of a 22-year sentence for multiple counts of rape and sexual offences against young girls, some as young as 12.</p><p>The government has indicated that Pakistan may face visa restrictions if it does not agree to take back Ahmed, who has been stripped of his British citizenship. Mahmood stated that she would amend the Immigration and Asylum Bill to remove legal protections that currently prevent his deportation under the 1971 Immigration Act. However, she acknowledged that deportation is contingent on Pakistan&#x27;s cooperation.</p><p>Ahmed&#x27;s release has sparked public outcry, particularly among victims and local councillors. Rochdale councillors have unanimously called for his deportation, urging the government to close the legal loophole that allows him to remain in the UK. Council leader Neil Emmott described Ahmed as an &#x27;evil man&#x27; and expressed the need for him to be removed from the country.</p><p>In response to the situation, Pakistan&#x27;s foreign office has stated that the responsibility for Ahmed&#x27;s actions lies with the UK, where he was raised and groomed. The Pakistani government has indicated it will not accept his return, complicating the UK government&#x27;s efforts to deport him.</p><p>A case involving a grooming gang in Rochdale has prompted the leader of the Green Party to question the deportation of a key figure associated with the group.</p><p>The comments come amid ongoing discussions about the handling of grooming gang cases in the UK, particularly in light of previous controversies surrounding the treatment of victims and offenders.</p><p>The Green leader&#x27;s remarks have reignited debates about the effectiveness of current policies and the implications for community safety and justice.</p><h2>Update timeline</h2><ul><li><strong>20 July 2026, 11:30:</strong> Home Secretary to Amend Law to Deport Rochdale Grooming Gang Ringleader</li><li><strong>14 July 2026, 01:01:</strong> Man Arrested Following Thefts in Bamford Area</li></ul>",
